INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (468,1,'2013-05-28 14:41:08','2013-05-28 18:41:08','<p class=\"p1\">This means your Mac can’t find a disk with the proper software to start. While not a terribly common issue, you should first check that your computer is trying to boot from the correct drive; to do so, hold down the Option key immediately after you press the power button to turn your computer on, and then select the drive where your operating system is installed (usually “Macintosh HD”). Past that, there are a few things you can try, but these computers often wind up at Tekserve for data recovery. First, <a title=\"How do I reset the PRAM/NVRAM?\" href=\"http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=317\">try to zap the PRAM/NVRAM</a>. If that doesn’t work, see <a title=\"How do I repair my Mac’s hard drive using Disk Utility?\" href=\"http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=306\"><em>How do I repair my Mac’s hard drive using Disk Utility?</em></a>. If none of those steps work, you will probably need to bring your computer in for repair.</p>','I turned on my computer and just see a little blinking prohibitory symbol (a \"no smoking\" sign without the cigarette), a flashing question mark, or a blinking folder and happy face.','','inherit','open','open','','310-autosave','','','2013-05-28 14:41:08','2013-05-28 18:41:08','',310,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=468',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (469,1,'2013-05-23 19:09:27','2013-05-23 23:09:27','<p class=\"p1\">This means your Mac can&rsquo;t find a disk with the proper software to start. While not a terribly common issue, you should first check that your computer is trying to boot from the correct drive; to do so, hold down the Option key immediately after you press the power button to turn your computer on, and then select the drive where your operating system is installed (usually &ldquo;Macintosh HD&rdquo;). Past that, there are a few things you can try, but these computers often wind up at Tekserve for data recovery. First, try to zap the PRAM/NVRAM (see below). If that doesn&rsquo;t work, see <em>How do I repair my Mac&rsquo;s hard drive using Disk Utility?</em> below. If none of those steps work, you will probably need to bring your computer in for repair.</p>','I turned on my computer and just see a little blinking prohibitory symbol (a \"no smoking\" sign without the cigarette), a flashing question mark, or a blinking folder and happy face.','','inherit','open','open','','310-revision-2','','','2013-05-23 19:09:27','2013-05-23 23:09:27','',310,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=469',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (470,1,'2013-05-28 14:44:35','2013-05-28 18:44:35','<p class=\"p1\">1. If you use an Ethernet cable, unplug it and restart. If the Mac starts up, you should carefully check your network preferences for incorrect information.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">2. Unplug any external devices from your system and restart.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">3. Check for old and incompatible third-party startup items, preference panes, and login items. Perform a Safe Boot (see below), and look in the following places for items you may have previously installed.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Drag the suspects to the desktop to disable them. If you are unsure, it is best to leave the item in place. The likely suspects:</p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><em>Note:</em></strong><em> Read <a title=\"I don’t know what any of these computery words mean!\" href=\"./?p=250\">the section on </a></em><a title=\"I don’t know what any of these computery words mean!\" href=\"./?p=250\"><em>file paths</em></a><em> if you’re not sure how to navigate to these items.</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">• Preference Panes: <em>Macintosh HD/Library/PreferencePanes</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><em>• Macintosh HD/Users/YourName/Library/PreferencePanes </em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">• Startup Items: <em>Macintosh HD/Library/StartupItems</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><em>• Macintosh HD/Library/Launch Agents</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><em>• Macintosh HD/Library/LaunchDemons</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><em>• Macintosh HD/Users/YourName/Library/ Launch Agents </em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">• Login Items: Open<em> System Preferences</em>, click<em> Accounts or Users &amp; Groups, </em>then<em> Login Items</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">If you’re running Lion or later, <a href=\"http://www.tekserve.com/faqs/annoyances.html\">see <em>How do I access the Library folder?</em></a>.</p>','When I start up my Mac it stays on a blue screen for hours and never shows me the desktop.','','inherit','open','open','','308-autosave','','','2013-05-28 14:44:35','2013-05-28 18:44:35','',308,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=470',0,'revision','',0);
