INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (553,1,'2013-05-28 17:30:06','2013-05-28 21:30:06','<p class=\"p1\">The background processes that use the most power are the device’s being on and being awake, the screen brightness, location-tracking, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, push notifications, auto-checking of many mail accounts, and the built-in speakers. So: Turn off Wi-Fi when you’re not using it, turn on Auto-Brightness so the level reacts to ambient light, and set a short Auto-Sleep interval. (They’re all in Settings.)</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><em>Note:</em></strong><em> These things let you squeeze more time out of a battery charge. Optimizing the overall lifetime of the battery is something else, and you’ll find details at the links below. But the most important one is: Run the battery through a complete charge cycle once a month—use it until it’s drained, and then recharge it completely.</em></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Check our further advice at our website, and more details at <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/ipad.html\">apple.com/batteries/ipad.html</a>, <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/ipods.html\">apple.com/batteries/ipods.html</a>, and <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/iphone.html\">apple.com/batteries/iphone.html</a>.</p>','How do I make my battery last longer? ','','publish','open','open','','how-do-i-make-my-battery-last-longer','','','2013-05-28 17:30:06','2013-05-28 21:30:06','',0,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=553',59,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (554,1,'2013-05-28 17:28:55','2013-05-28 21:28:55','<p class=\"p1\">The background processes that use the most power are the device’s being on and being awake, the screen brightness, location-tracking, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, push notifications, auto-checking of many mail accounts, and the built-in speakers. So: Turn off Wi-Fi when you’re not using it, turn on Auto-Brightness so the level reacts to ambient light, and set a short Auto-Sleep interval. (They’re all in Settings.)</p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><em>Note:</em></strong><em> These things let you squeeze more time out of a battery charge. Optimizing the overall lifetime of the battery is something else, and you’ll find details at the links below. But the most important one is: Run the battery through a complete charge cycle once a month—use it until it’s drained, and then recharge it completely.</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Check our further advice at our website, and more details at <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/ipad.html\">apple.com/batteries/ipad.html</a>, <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/ipods.html\">apple.com/batteries/ipods.html</a>, and <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/iphone.html\">apple.com/batteries/iphone.html</a>.</p>','How do I make my battery last longer? ','','inherit','open','open','','553-revision','','','2013-05-28 17:28:55','2013-05-28 21:28:55','',553,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=554',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (555,1,'2013-05-23 16:15:17','2013-05-23 20:15:17','<p class=\"p1\">That depends. First, if you&rsquo;ve just about depleted the battery, it may need to charge for up to twenty minutes before you can even turn it on. Next, it depends on how much usage you&rsquo;re talking about (a quick look at something, accessing a network, full-screen brightness web browsing?) and how much charging you&rsquo;re doing (low- or high-wattage adapter, USB port on your computer?).</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>iPad:</strong> The iPad&rsquo;s larger battery, and greater power consumption when in use, means that the things that generally drain an iDevice&rsquo;s battery (<span class=\"s1\"><strong>See <em>H</em></strong></span><strong><em>ow do I make my battery last longer? b</em>elow</strong>) can slurp out almost as much juice as you&rsquo;re putting in&mdash;sometimes, even <em>more</em>&mdash;if you&rsquo;re charging from a computer. This is especially true of the iPad 3 and 4, whose retina screens are power-hungry. If you must use your iPad but you also need to charge it from your computer, keep the brightness down, and network usage to a minimum.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>iPhone/Touch:</strong> The iPhone/Touch is much less demanding when it comes to power, so you&rsquo;ll be able to charge it and use it at the same time, although heavy use can add to the charge time.</p>','Can I use my iDevice while it\'s charging?','','inherit','open','open','','153-revision-4','','','2013-05-23 16:15:17','2013-05-23 20:15:17','',153,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=555',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (556,1,'2013-05-28 17:30:43','2013-05-28 21:30:43','<p class=\"p1\">That depends. First, if you’ve just about depleted the battery, it may need to charge for up to twenty minutes before you can even turn it on. Next, it depends on how much usage you’re talking about (a quick look at something, accessing a network, full-screen brightness web browsing?) and how much charging you’re doing (low- or high-wattage adapter, USB port on your computer?).</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>iPad:</strong> The iPad’s larger battery, and greater power consumption when in use, means that the things that generally drain an iDevice’s battery (<span class=\"s1\"><strong>See <a title=\"How do I make my battery last longer?\" href=\"./?p=553\"><em>H</em></a></strong></span><a title=\"How do I make my battery last longer?\" href=\"./?p=553\"><strong><em>ow do I make my battery last longer?</em></strong></a>) can slurp out almost as much juice as you’re putting in—sometimes, even <em>more</em>—if you’re charging from a computer. This is especially true of the iPad 3 and 4, whose retina screens are power-hungry. If you must use your iPad but you also need to charge it from your computer, keep the brightness down, and network usage to a minimum.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>iPhone/Touch:</strong> The iPhone/Touch is much less demanding when it comes to power, so you’ll be able to charge it and use it at the same time, although heavy use can add to the charge time.</p>','Can I use my iDevice while it\'s charging?','','inherit','open','open','','153-revision-5','','','2013-05-28 17:30:43','2013-05-28 21:30:43','',153,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=556',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (557,1,'2013-05-28 17:31:07','2013-05-28 21:31:07','<p class=\"p1\">The background processes that use the most power are the device’s being on and being awake, the screen brightness, location-tracking, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, push notifications, auto-checking of many mail accounts, and the built-in speakers. So: Turn off Wi-Fi when you’re not using it, turn on Auto-Brightness so the level reacts to ambient light, and set a short Auto-Sleep interval. (They’re all in Settings.)</p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><em>Note:</em></strong><em> These things let you squeeze more time out of a battery charge. Optimizing the overall lifetime of the battery is something else, and you’ll find details at the links below. But the most important one is: Run the battery through a complete charge cycle once a month—use it until it’s drained, and then recharge it completely.</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Check our further advice at our website, and more details at <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/ipad.html\">apple.com/batteries/ipad.html</a>, <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/ipods.html\">apple.com/batteries/ipods.html</a>, and <a href=\"apple.com/batteries/iphone.html\">apple.com/batteries/iphone.html</a>.</p>','How do I make my battery last longer? ','','inherit','open','open','','553-autosave','','','2013-05-28 17:31:07','2013-05-28 21:31:07','',553,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=557',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (558,1,'2013-05-23 16:15:44','2013-05-23 20:15:44','<p class=\"p1\">There are so many variables, there&rsquo;s no set answer. The fastest way to charge your iDevice is by turning it off&mdash;or at least putting it to sleep&mdash;and plugging it into an outlet using the power adapter and cable. This can recharge an iPad in 6-7 hours, and an iPhone/Touch in just a couple of hours. Using the iDevice while it&rsquo;s charging, or charging it through a computer connection, adds to the charge time.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong><em>Warning!</em></strong><em> The adapter you use affects the charging time. If you have multiple devices and adapters, using a higher-wattage adapter (the &ldquo;bricks&rdquo; are interchangeable) shortens charging time somewhat. The iPad 4 has a 12-watt adapter; earlier iPads, 10 and 12 watts; iPhone/Touch and iPad Mini, 5 watts.</em></p>','How long does it take to charge my iDevice?','','inherit','open','open','','151-revision-3','','','2013-05-23 16:15:44','2013-05-23 20:15:44','',151,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=558',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (559,1,'2013-05-23 16:16:09','2013-05-23 20:16:09','<p class=\"p1\">It depends. USB ports don&rsquo;t provide a charge if the computer is off or sleeping, so you&rsquo;d have to leave it on. A port in a standalone display that&rsquo;s left on (even if it&rsquo;s sleeping) will likely work, as would a powered USB hub. Check by connecting your iDevice and seeing if the battery icon in the status bar shows it&rsquo;s charging.</p>','Can I charge my iDevice overnight by leaving it attached to my computer?','','inherit','open','open','','149-revision-3','','','2013-05-23 16:16:09','2013-05-23 20:16:09','',149,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=559',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (560,1,'2013-05-28 17:33:42','2013-05-28 21:33:42','<p class=\"p1\">It depends. USB ports don’t provide a charge if the computer is off or sleeping, so you’d have to leave it on. A port in a standalone display that’s left on (even if it’s sleeping) will likely work, as would a powered USB hub. Check by connecting your iDevice and seeing if the battery icon in the status bar shows it’s charging.</p>','Can I charge my iDevice overnight by leaving it attached to my computer?','','inherit','open','open','','149-autosave','','','2013-05-28 17:33:42','2013-05-28 21:33:42','',149,'http://localhost/tekfaqs/?p=560',0,'revision','',0);
